## PostgreSQL API: migrate, run server, run web client

### 1. Install backend dependencies (once)

```powershell
npm install --prefix backend
```

### 2. Configure environment

Use the right env file for the target database:

| Target | Env file | Migrate command |
|--------|----------|-----------------|
| Staging | `.env.staging` | `npm run db:migrate:staging` |
| Production | `.env.production` | `npm run db:migrate:production` |
| Dev / legacy | `.env` | `npm run db:migrate:lan` |

### 3. Run database migrations

```powershell
npm run db:migrate:staging
npm run db:migrate:production
```

SQL files in `database/migrations/` are applied in order (see `backend/src/migrate.ts`).

### 4. Run the API server

```powershell
npm run dev:backend:staging       # staging, tsx watch, port 3001
npm run start:backend:staging     # staging, compiled

npm run dev:backend:production    # production, tsx watch, port 3000
npm run start:backend:production  # production, compiled
```

- Staging health: `http://127.0.0.1:3001/health`
- Production health: `http://127.0.0.1:3000/health`

### 5. Run the web client against the API

```powershell
npm run dev
```

For **Desktop Edition (PostgreSQL)**, use `npm run test:local-only` or `npm run test:staging`.

One-off SQLite migration scripts remain under `tools/legacy/` — see `tools/legacy/README.md`.

